# Manual Control 🕹️

Included in `System.Threading`.

```csharp
using System.Threading;

void Print() {
    Console.WriteLine("Running on new thread!");
}

Thread t = new Thread(Print);
t.Start(); // Moves 'Print' to separate thread

Console.WriteLine("Main thread continues...");
```

# The Danger Zone ⚠️

If two threads modify the same variable at the same time, data gets corrupted (Race Condition).

## The Lock
Use `lock` to ensure only one thread enters a block at a time.

```csharp
object _lock = new object();

lock (_lock) {
    // Only one thread can be here at a time
    count++;
}
```

# The Modern Way 🚀

`Thread` is heavy. `Task` is light and optimized. Use `System.Threading.Tasks`.

```csharp
Task.Run(() => {
    Console.WriteLine("Heavy work...");
});
```
Tasks use a "Thread Pool" to manage resources efficiently.

# Asynchronous Programming ⏳

Best for I/O (File, DB, Web) where the CPU just waits.

1.  **`async`**: Marks a method as asynchronous.
2.  **`await`**: Pauses execution *without blocking* the thread until task finishes.

```csharp
public async Task DownloadData() {
    // Waits here, but UI stays responsive!
    await Task.Delay(2000); 
    Console.WriteLine("Done!");
}
```

